ed crops like palm oil, safflower or others, depending upon your soil & climate conditions.  These 'food oils' can be easily converted to biodiesel, another carbon-neutral fuel.    If it's windy where you are, your farm could include a windmill farm.    If the market for biofuel is not good, you could also have an integrated co-generation plant for production of electricity directly from gasified biomass.  Then your end product would be electricity.    The byproducts of biomass gasification are solids that make good fertilizer that you could re-use on your crops and/or sell.  Also, there is a lot of clean steam coming off of a gasifier that could be reclaimed as 'distilled' water if you put a heat exchanger (condenser) on the exhaust.  This could be used for irrigation or even potable water, under the right circumstances.
